Both beveling and fencing are techniques that help support the shape of a mesh when smoothed. If a mesh allows its bevel info go all the way through, then beveling is the fastest way to add supporting loops before smoothing it. Fencing, however, means we are adding the supporting loops manually. As shown before, beveling sometimes introduces minor artifacts and fencing has a lower chance of doing that.  

Here are some more differences between beveling and fencing. 

For geo to go through vertically and horizontally, bevel and insert edge loop would produce fairly even result. 

With beveling, it loses somewhat more volume. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

With fencing, it only loses a tiny amount of volume. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

For geo to go diagonal direction, bevel and insert edge loop would produce uneven result, and might require a manual adjustment. However it saves a lot of polygon count. 

With beveling, it still loses somewhat more volume. 

With fencing, it still loses just a tiny amount of volume. 

So the conclusion are: 

If minor artifact doesn't cause a issue, use beveling. 

If polygon count doesn't cause a issue, use vertical and horizontal geo and beveling. 

If we have to use fencing, do it with a diagonal geo is faster and saves poly count.
